04868nam a22008655i 9780674418394DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20131996mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013954774  a97806744183947 a10.4159/harvard.97806744183942doi  a(DE-B1597)252724  a(OCoLC)900806454  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aB2599.J8 7aBIO0090002bisacsh04a172.2092  aCF 55172rvk0(DE-625)rvk/18113:116161 aRiley, Patrick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLeibniz' Universal Jurisprudence :bJustice as the Charity of the Wise /cPatrick Riley.  aReprint 2014 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (338 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Leibniz Translations -- tIntroduction -- t1 Foundations -- t2 Monadology and Justice -- t3 Theodicy as Universal Justice -- t4 Justice as Love and Benevolence -- t5 Practical Justice in the Human Forum -- t6 The Republic of Christendom -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough Leibniz is universally regarded as the greatest German philosopher before Kant, his work as a political and moral philosopher is almost entirely neglected in the English-speaking world, where he is seen chiefly as a metaphysician, mathematical logician, and co-discoverer of calculus. Yet Leibniz' doctoral degree was in law and jurisprudence, and he served throughout his life as a judge and a diplomat; he was a valued political--legal adviser to Czar Peter the Great, to the King of Prussia in Berlin, and to the Holy Roman Emperor in Vienna. Patrick Riley recovers this crucial part of Leibniz' thought and activity. For the first time--as we celebrate the 350th anniversary of Leibniz' birth--his political, moral, and legal thought are extensively discussed here in English. The text includes fragments of his work that have never before been translated. Riley shows that "justice as wise charity" has at least as much claim to be taken seriously as the familiar contractarian ideas of Hobbes and Locke. Since Leibniz was the greatest Platonist of early modernity, Riley argues, his version of Platonic idealism serves as the bridge from Plato himself to the greatest modern "critical" idealist, Kant. With Leibniz' Universal Jurisprudence we now have a fuller picture of one of the greatest general thinkers of the seventeenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEthics, Modern. 0aLove. 0aPhilosophie. 0aPolitieke filosofie. 0aRechtsfilosofie. 0aRechtvaardigheid. 4aEthics, Modern -- 17th century. 4aJustice (Philosophy) -- History -- 17th century. 4aLeibniz, Gottfried Wilhelm, Freiherr von, 1646-1716. 4aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy. 4aPHILOSOPHY / Political. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Philosophers.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Philosophy eBook Packagez9783110353525oZDB-23-HPI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067441837040uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067441839440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674418394423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674418394.jpg  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB